      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The peak areas of compounds and IS, if applicable, need to be exported for use in mzQuality. We strongly recommend using a tab-separated format while exporting... The input file should include the following columns with the specified headers (Table ): aliquot, type, batch, compound, area, and datetime of the sample measurement.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms tab-separated input format and SCIEX OS export (passage 4: 'The data were integrated using SCIEX OS (version 2.1.6.59781) and exported using the recommended data format'). However, no mention of SummarizedExperiment objects, doAnalysis, createReports, or any Bioconductor container structure. mzQuality reads tab-delimited files directly without intermediate object construction.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-jasms-5c00073",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "r-bioconductor-summarizedexperiment-manipulation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When converting raw metabolomics data (tab-delimited text files, Sciex OS exports) into a structured object for batch processing, or when you need to organize compound-level measurements (assays), sample metadata (colData), and feature annotations (rowData) in a single container ",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
